Humming Eagle,<br><br>
You ask a very good question, what kind if food am I gathering? <br><br>
The story brings out those unfortunate connections with things to which we cling even though we know them to be bad for us, through pity for ouselves, through fear, through emptiness, through countless other hollow life draining reasons, 'Nam reasons.<br><br>
It is clear to me that only I must be the master of my destiny if I am to achieve balance, and not the snake. The snake, after all, is eternally devouring its own tail. The snake also sheds its skin, and, funny, you still end up with a snake!<br><br>
I.<br>
I am. <br>
I am someone.<br>
I am someone worthy.<br>
I am someone worthy of life.<br>
I am someone worthy of life who thinks.<br><br>
This is food for the White Wolf!<br><br>
Hecito Yelo? I think so....<br><br>
A wise friend once told me that insanity is thinking (doing) the same thing over and over again, and expecting different results each time.<br><br>
He, too, was right.<br><br>
Thanks,<br><br>
Art
